                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d868">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/12791.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Brazilian Minister</gloss> to Mexico to
                        the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Brazilian Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-09T18:00:00-06:36">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 9, 1914, 6 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I communicated to the President the contents of your August 9, 4 p.m., but I
                    think it is too late because this morning General Obregon, who is very near
                    Mexico City, sent a message asking unconditional surrender. The President and
                    the Army are willing to comply with the request, the Army being ready to
                    evacuate the city without fighting. The President and Carranza’s agent, Robles,
                    have requested the good offices of the Diplomatic Corps, especially mine, to
                    help them facilitate occupation of the capital by Constitutionalists without
                    either friction with the Federals or disturbance of public order. The Diplomatic
                    Corps will study the matter tonight.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cardoso de Oliveira</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
